GLMs for Categorical Data

A Modern Machine Learning Definition: It is a classification algorithm used to assign observations to a discrete set of classes.

Types of logistic regression:

  • Binary (e.g. Pass/Fail)
  • Multiple (e.g. Cats, Dogs, Sheep)
  • Ordinal (e.g. Low, Medium, High)

We will focus on binary outcomes today.

Use of Logistic Regression in Medicine

Question: What is the binary outcome here?

Today's Case Study

Data: Contraceptive use data of 1607 currently married and fertile women interviewed in the Fiji Fertility Survey. Source: Princeton's WWS 509

Data descriptors in the next page.

Today's Case Study

Data: Contraceptive use data of 1607 currently married and fertile women interviewed in the Fiji Fertility Survey. Source: Princeton's WWS 509

Covariates:

  • Contraceptive Use: 1 if using, 0 if not.
  • Age:
    • 1 if \( age < 25 \), 2 if \( 25 \leq age < 30 \),
    • 3 if \( 30 \leq age < 40 \), 4 if \( 40 \leq age < 50 \)
  • Education: 1 if 'high education', 2 if 'low education'.
  • Want More Children: 1 if yes, 2 if no

Today's Case Study

proc freq data = contraceptive;
table ContraceptiveUse Age Education WantsMore; 
run;

Always good to check your data!

Multiple Logistic Regression

Logistic in SAS

SAS Code: Make sure to include descending so 1 is treated as binary outcome of interest

proc logistic data = contraceptive descending;
class Age (ref = '1') Education (ref = '0') WantsMore (ref = '0');
model ContraceptiveUse = Age Education WantsMore;
run;

Predictive Power

  • Sensitivity: \( P(\hat{y} = 1| y =1) \)

  • Specificity: \( P(\hat{y} = 0| y =0) \)

  • Receiver operating characteristics (ROC) curve: a plot of sensitivity vs. (1-specificity)

  • Area under the curve (AUC): area under the ROC curve

Let us view an example in the next page.

Some of Work in Social Media Analytics

ROC in SAS

Add to your current code: outroc = ROCData

proc logistic data = contraceptive descending;
model ContraceptiveUse = (your covariates) / outroc = ROCData;
run;

What is the area under the curve?

Goodness of Fit

Hosmer-Lemeshow test: A statistical test for goodness of fit for logistic regression model. Assesses whether or not the observed event rates match expected event rates in subgroups of the model population. Ho: observed and expected proportions are the same across all doses (good fit). Ha: : observed and expected proportions differ significantly (lack of fit).

proc logistic data = contraceptive descending;
model ContraceptiveUse =  (your covariates) / lackfit; run;

Goodness of Fit Output

What is the area under the curve?

Ho: observed and expected proportions are the same across all doses (good fit). Ha: : observed and expected proportions differ significantly (lack of fit). Conclusion: We reject the null and conclude that the model does not accurately predict the probability of contraceptive use.
